		<description><![CDATA[I have just been informed by a Tweet that Teachers TV will be made available for download by the TES in the near future. In fact they have a very small selection of the archive up already at: http://www.tes.co.uk/article.aspx?storyCode=6081871&#38;s_cid=RESads_TTVvideos but still none available for download I can see. So along with Teachers Media (the people [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>I have just been informed by a Tweet that Teachers TV will be made available for <a href="http://www.tes.co.uk/article.aspx?storyCode=6081387&amp;s_cid=RESads_TTVvideos" target="_blank">download by the TES</a> in the near future.</p>
<p>In fact they have a very small selection of the archive up already at:</p>
<p><a href="http://www.tes.co.uk/article.aspx?storyCode=6081871&amp;s_cid=RESads_TTVvideos" target="_blank">http://www.tes.co.uk/article.aspx?storyCode=6081871&amp;s_cid=RESads_TTVvideos</a></p>
<p>but still none available for download I can see.</p>
<p>So along with <a title="Teachers Media " href="http://www.teachersmedia.co.uk/" target="_blank">Teachers Media</a> (the people behind making TeachersTV) and Ten Alps <a title="Schoolsworld" href="http://www.schoolsworld.tv/" target="_blank">SchoolsWorld</a> TV (a former Teachers TV investor) and a host of other companies yet to declare, it seems we are spoiled for choice. I am sure the market will decide which flavour of the resource is best and most useful in tandem with, other, new, resources.</p>
<p>However if you have been involved in the<a title="Twitter hashtag for #saveTTV" href="http://twitter.com/#!/search/%23saveTTV" target="_blank"> #saveTTV </a>campaign <strong><em>I should still upload your files if asked to</em></strong>, as the TES and other companies have yet to clarify their exact position on this.</p>
<p>Obviously, if all companies are going to make files available for download then the campaign becomes redundant. But, in the meantime, people can see what the archives comprises of by going to the spreadsheet at:</p>
<p><a title="Teachers TV Archive Spreadsheet" href="https://spreadsheets.google.com/ccc?key=0AqOhBi9yGR1LdHlYREszU0I5anRHX2tVM0VPLWZhWmc&amp;hl=en_GB#gid=0" target="_blank">https://spreadsheets.google.com/ccc?key=0AqOhBi9yGR1LdHlYREszU0I5anRHX2tVM0VPLWZhWmc&amp;hl=en_GB#gid=0</a></p>
<p>and requesting access.</p>
<p><em><strong>We now have a fair percentage of the archive collated and available for peer to peer distribution as a stopgap. So please, if you are asked to, please continue to upload the files</strong></em>.</p>
<p>What this whole campaign has proved is that Teachers put an extremely high value on resources made for, about and with them &#8211; in the latter stages of Teachers TV the company was also helping teachers make their own programmes as in the<strong><em> Action! Teacher Video series</em></strong>.</p>
<p>I would like to thank everyone for their amazing work on highlighting the archive as an amazing resource and helping to bring the possible demise of the programmes to the attention of the wider teaching community.</p>
<p>As an exercise in crowdsourcing and direct action it was incredibly successful and shows what a dedicated group of teachers can do when they set their minds to it.</p>
<p>Watch this space for further news and developments.</p>
