		<description><![CDATA[cc Licence from niallkennedy on Flickr I&#8217;m here at the marvellous Learning Without Frontiers conference and I&#8217;m multitasking with streaming, twittering and closely observing all the presenters and it&#8217;s a bit like the blind men and the elephant all over again. Each presenter has one part of the solution but no-one seems to be stating [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="http://farm1.static.flickr.com/23/40727794_d95dc73ecb.jpg"><img class="alignnone" src="http://farm1.static.flickr.com/23/40727794_d95dc73ecb.jpg" alt="" width="500" height="333" /></a></p>
<p><em>cc Licence from <a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/niallkennedy/40727794/sizes/m/in/photostream/" target="_blank">niallkennedy</a> on Flickr</em></p>
<p>I&#8217;m here at the marvellous <a href="http://www.learningwithoutfrontiers.co" target="_blank">Learning Without Frontiers conference</a> and I&#8217;m multitasking with streaming, twittering and closely observing all the presenters and it&#8217;s a bit like <a href="http://www.noogenesis.com/pineapple/blind_men_elephant.html" target="_blank">the blind men and the elephant</a> all over again. Each presenter has one part of the solution but no-one seems to be stating the obvious.</p>
<p><a href="http://twitter.com/#!/edvaizey" target="_blank">Ed Vaizey</a> is here representing the government. Disregarding the fact that the DfE wasn&#8217;t represented here at all, he made a good fist of trying to understand the landscape. He mentioned the NESTA research into <a href="http://www.nesta.org.uk/press/assets/features/weakest_link_found_in_subjects_necessary_for_careers_in_video_games_and_visual_effects" target="_blank">Gaming and Education </a>with an emphasis on lack of understanding of the role of Academic Subjects in Gaming but what he didn&#8217;t point out was this other scheme which is focused on the <a href="http://www.nesta.org.uk/areas_of_work/creative_industries/hyper_island" target="_blank">Creative Industries</a>; maybe the &#8220;softer&#8221; subjects don&#8217;t count or no-one had bothered to find out or promote this side of what NESTA is doing, to him?</p>
<p>Never mind &#8211; I&#8217;m not one to nitpick I&#8217;m more interested in practical strategies that will work or at least have a possibility of making change happen rather worrying about government ed policy in this area. Ed&#8217;s argument that the Games industry happened despite there being no kit in schools is true. In the early 80&#8242;s &#8211; if you had the money &#8211; you could buy a cheap home computer and you could teach yourself to program on it &#8211; few schools had them. But the problem is now that if there are no computers at school and if you don&#8217;t have one at home then where are you going to get access? Well I remember back in the early 90&#8242;s &#8211; young children in my class didn&#8217;t have a computer but in central London they paid for access themselves at the early computer cafes.</p>
<p>Next up was Derek Robertson showing wonderful videos about children&#8217;s expertise in the home with Gaming Kit. One question he was asked was about teachers being able to cope with lots of children who want to learn about gaming, game construction and then I kind of lost it&#8230;</p>
<p>The teachers don&#8217;t have the expertise to deal with this?!! So what we have is a situation where kids are frisked for their skills at the school gates.</p>
<p>&#8220;What&#8217;s that you got there? Oh it&#8217;s a piece of knowledge and expertise I don&#8217;t understand/can&#8217;t manage &#8211; that&#8217;s dangerous &#8211; empty out your pockets and, possibly your head.&#8221; Unfair &#8211; I know but Derek clearly shows that the skills, knowledge, expertise are IN THE HOME so why not focus on that arena and co-opt it with the school. Why are we still thinking in terms of institutional vs community silos?</p>
<p>OK so I have been thinking about what would level the playing field and open out the opportunities for learning. Well it would seem to me that it isn&#8217;t about devices any more &#8211; it is about connectivity and the social contracts and spaces real or virtual, around that.</p>
<p>Her&#8217;s one model:</p>
<p><a href="http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/click_online/9294368.stm" target="_blank">http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/click_online/9294368.stm</a></p>
<p>Now imagine it is about the connectivity and access rather than silos and gatekeeping?</p>
<p>Number one &#8211; the divisions between home and school are brought in under the same umbrella so some of them can be managed one and the same.</p>
<p>Number two &#8211; the learning space between home and school is connected &#8211; never mind VLEs &#8211; you can have those if you want but so long as you have the connectivity you can put whatever device or platform (even a gaming one) you want on it. What is more important is how you manage the community?</p>
<p>This necessarily means moving the focus around as well &#8211; sometimes into the home where the kids can show their expertise &#8211; where they are most comfortable in showing expertise. At other times in the school &#8211; at other times elsewhere; in virtual and real arenas. Let&#8217;s mix it up.</p>
<p>Number three &#8211; have a community learning manager as well as a head teacher- change people&#8217;s roles. What would that entail?</p>
<p>How about this &#8211; building community &#8211; putting in management services to enable learning where learning is happening. Sort out licensing, e-safety and e-community footprints. Teach digital literacy awareness &#8211; build alternate spaces that move to where the &#8220;real&#8221; learning is happening and facilitate that. Build a workable foundation that enables rather than blocks &#8211; how many people would relish that challenge?</p>
<p>Yes &#8211; make the school a social and academic hub but extend out and embrace the local area and make transparent how people learn. Notice I am not talking about kit here &#8211; if you are truly wired into your community &#8211; you are agile enough, innovative enough, flexible enough to adapt to any system and you teach that too, and make that process transparent to others and you will learn to build in those systems if you have connectivity being ubiquitous and commutative between different physical spaces.</p>
<p>You don&#8217;t frisk the kids &#8211; you invite them in &#8211; you embrace their skills and you make that learning and how you enable that learning, transparent to everyone else and bring them along with you. Remember we are all in this together&#8230;</p>
<p>It&#8217;s about how well you bring people together; how quick you can think on your feet; how well you manage other people.</p>
<p>Get commercial firms to sponsor connectivity, take the focus away from the school and bring it into the wider community. Build new jobs and roles around this new larger scope with a wider vision of what education and learning could mean?</p>
<p>Yes &#8211; Learning Without Frontiers &#8211; but let&#8217;s start with our own back yard.</p>
